        "text": "<p><strong>“Your stomach isn’t broken,” my digestive specialist said gently.</strong></p><p>“What you’re experiencing is called post-meal digestive slowdown. And it’s extremely common for women after 35.”</p><p>She pulled out her notebook—that familiar scratch of pen against paper—and leaned in closer.</p><p>“Let me show you what may be happening.”</p><p>She drew three simple circles.</p><p><strong>“First, digestion can naturally start slowing down with age.</strong> Think of it like your stomach taking longer to process heavier meals than it used to.”</p><p><strong>“Second, your gut balance may begin changing over time.</strong> Stress, medications, processed foods, and everyday lifestyle habits can affect the balance of good bacteria in the digestive system.”</p><p><strong>“And third—this is important—many women become more sensitive to foods they used to tolerate just fine.”</strong></p><p>“Wait,” I interrupted. “So it’s not just overeating? Or me doing something wrong?”</p><p>“Exactly.” She smiled.</p>",
